{"id":"cond-mat/0303635","submitter":"Bernhard Mehlig","authors":"M. Wilkinson and B. Mehlig","title":"Path Coalescence in Spatially Correlated Random Walks","comments":"This manuscript was superseded by cond-mat/0305491 [Phys. Rev. E 68,\n  040101 (2003)]","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech cond-mat.dis-nn","license":null,"abstract":"  A particle subject to successive, random displacements is said to execute a\nrandom walk (in position or some other coordinate). The mathematical properties\nof random walks have been very thoroughly investigated, and the model is used\nin many areas of science and engineering as well as other fields such as\nfinance and the life sciences. This letter describes a phenomenon occurring in\na natural extension of this model: we consider the motion of a large number of\nparticles subject to successive random displacements which are correlated in\nspace, but not in time. If these random displacements are smaller than their\ncorrelation length, the trajectories coalesce onto a decreasing number of\ntrails. This surprising effect is explained and quantitative results are\nobtained. Various possible realisations are discussed, ranging from coalescence\nof the tracks of water droplets blown off a windshield to migration patterns of\nanimals.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 31 Mar 2003 10:04:44 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 25 Oct 2003 15:56:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
