{"id":"quant-ph/0303182","submitter":"Jonathan Barrett","authors":"Jonathan Barrett and Serge Massar","title":"Quantum coin tossing and bit-string generation in the presence of noise","comments":"REVTeX. 6 pages, no figures. Early versions contained errors in\n  statements of security conditions, although results were correct. v4: PRA\n  version","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 69, 022322 (2004)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.69.022322","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We discuss the security implications of noise for quantum coin tossing\nprotocols. We find that if quantum error correction can be used, so that noise\nlevels can be made arbitrarily small, then reasonable security conditions for\ncoin tossing can be framed so that results from the noiseless case will\ncontinue to hold. If, however, error correction is not available (as is the\ncase with present day technology), and significant noise is present, then\ntossing a single coin becomes problematic. In this case, we are led to consider\nrandom n-bit string generation in the presence of noise, rather than\nsingle-shot coin tossing. We introduce precise security criteria for n-bit\nstring generation and describe an explicit protocol that could be implemented\nwith present day technology. In general, a cheater can exploit noise in order\nto bias coins to their advantage. We derive explicit upper bounds on the\naverage bias achievable by a cheater for given noise levels.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 31 Mar 2003 11:57:25 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 4 Apr 2003 11:08:03 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 22 Oct 2003 15:51:52 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Fri, 2 Apr 2004 13:47:04 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-10"}
{"id":"quant-ph/0303183","submitter":"Marco Pravia","authors":"Marco A. Pravia, Zhiying Chen, Jeffrey Yepez, David G. Cory","title":"Experimental Demonstration of Quantum Lattice Gas Computation","comments":"20 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We report an ensemble nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) implementation of a\nquantum lattice gas algorithm for the diffusion equation. The algorithm employs\nan array of quantum information processors sharing classical information, a\nnovel architecture referred to as a type-II quantum computer. This concrete\nimplementation provides a test example from which to probe the strengths and\nlimitations of this new computation paradigm. The NMR experiment consists of\nencoding a mass density onto an array of 16 two-qubit quantum information\nprocessors and then following the computation through 7 time steps of the\nalgorithm. The results show good agreement with the analytic solution for\ndiffusive dynamics. We also describe numerical simulations of the NMR\nimplementation. The simulations aid in determining sources of experimental\nerrors, and they help define the limits of the implementation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 31 Mar 2003 14:25:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
{"id":"quant-ph/0303184","submitter":"BG Englert","authors":"Dagmar Bruss, Matthias Christandl, Artur Ekert, Berthold-Georg\n  Englert, Dagomir Kaszlikowski, Chiara Macchiavello","title":"Tomographic Quantum Cryptography: Equivalence of Quantum and Classical\n  Key Distillation","comments":"4 pages, 1 figure","journal-ref":"Physical Review Letters, vol. 91, art. 097901 (2003)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.91.097901","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  The security of a cryptographic key that is generated by communication\nthrough a noisy quantum channel relies on the ability to distill a shorter\nsecure key sequence from a longer insecure one. For an important class of\nprotocols, which exploit tomographically complete measurements on entangled\npairs of any dimension, we show that the noise threshold for classical\nadvantage distillation is identical with the threshold for quantum entanglement\ndistillation. As a consequence, the two distillation procedures are equivalent:\nneither offers a security advantage over the other.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 31 Mar 2003 15:45:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-10"}
